1 - Introduction¶

Project Name¶

Neuefische Capstone Project: 'DIE ZEIT' Churn Prediction

Description¶

The task of this data science project is it to perform a churn prediction based on the cancellations of previous years. So, basically answering the question 'Which customer is canceling his or her subscription within the next year?'. To answer this question a model should get trained with the data from previous years (after 2012) to predict the affinity of canceling per order.

This notebook contains the exploratory data analysis to gather initial information about the processed data set and preprocess the data for the next step of modeling.

The the target variable is churn.

Time Period¶

Project Start: 23/11/2020
Project End: 18/12/2020

Findings¶

Demographics:¶

  • Overall: Our duplicate & outlier cleaned dataframe has 156,428 observations
  • 48,356 (30.9%) customers in the sample are churning from their subscription
  • 69k Women (34%) are more likely to churn their subscription than 85k men (29%)
  • Lesedauer is basically the contract term and you can see higher chrun rates at 6m, 12m or 24m, decreasing over time with the max churn rate at 12m
  • The most loyal group of subscribers are the religious ones (Die Zeit Christ & Welt) with a churn rate of 14% but they only represent 5461 people
    • (converting people to christianity is not a feasible option)
  • Zeit Digital subscribers are more loyal (25% churn rate) than the print customers (36%)
    • for the sake of our forrests & churn rates we can try to prevent churning by turning print to digital users
    • Zeit Digital subscriptions are constantly growing, it's the future market
    • Production & distribution of digital product compared to print medium is way more cost effective & climate neutral
  • Payment Methods: People with direct debit are less likely to churn (22%) than people who pay via invoice (41%)
  • Payment Frequency: 2 payments dates a year lead to a churn rate of 42% compared to 25% for one payment/year, the fewer the better
  • Students: Only 10.5% of the subscribers are students and students are more likely to cancel their subscription (44%).
  • PLZ-Areas Within germany no big differences in the churn rates, 27% for the 7-Area against 32% for the 1-Area,
  • Iso-Codes: foreign countries are more likely to churn (AT: 6k subs with 39%), (CH: 10k subs with 35%)
  • Titel: Academic subscriber are less likely to churn (23%) compared to non-academics(32%), the minority group of people with a "different title" are most likely to churn (44%)

Count Features:¶

  • people with more than one subscription tend to churn less (28%) than people with a single subscription (34%)
  • people who tested their subscription before paying for it are less likely to churn (25% vs. 35%)

ZON - Features:¶

  • for every feature (except zon_sonstige), the churn rates for non-registered users are lower than for the users, who completed the registration.

E-Mailings:¶

  • E-Mailing & Newsletters have generally a negative effect on churning subscribers
  • the only E-Mailing that has fewer subscribers churning than the average is "Produkt News"

Our desired subscriber without loosing bigger target groups:¶

Is a Zeit Digital customer who pays via direct debit. A low payment frequency of a yearly or even 2 yearly turnus should be advertised by special discounts an offerings like a special "productnews" mailing. He probably has a academic degree but is not a student anymore.

auftrag_new_id --> Apparently, for one subscription several auftrag_new_id can be created.
zon-columns --> These zon-columns (ZeitOnline) are independant from the subscrition itself (you can be a subscripter and not be registered for ZeitOnline services)
cnt-columns --> This is the total amount of abos per user. You could for example get a new subscritpion for "Zeit Digital" but already be subscriptor of "Die Zeit" and "Zeit Magazin". If cnt_abo == 0 it means, that except for the new subscription, no further subscriptions exist.
nl-columns --> Count of registrations for the newsletters. In this dataset, not all newsletters are included. This explains the difference between the sum of nl_zeitbrief,nl_zeitshop and nl_zeitverlag_hamburg and nl_aktivitaet
reg-columns --> Count of registrations for these services. Independant from the features before

For the sake of consistency, we will rename some columns

lesedauer

  • For the time between subscription and cancellation, there is a clear trend to be observed.
  • At the end of every contract year (12 months, 24 months and so on), an increase of cancellations can be seen (take a look at the graph above).

But:

  • The lesedauer for non_churners is set on a randomly generated Date in 05/2019- 05/2020.
  • This leads in some cases to non-churners who subscribed in 2018 having a shorter "lesedauer" than people who subscribed in 2018 and churned in 2019.
  • Therefore we create a new feature Vertragsdauer in 5. Feature Enginnering and repeat the analysis.

There doesn't seem to be a consistent link between the registrations and the number of churns. For zon_zp_grey for example, the churn rate is the lowest for the non-registered users and the highest for these, who completed the registration (same for zon_zp_red).

Another interesting finding here is, that for every feature here (except for zon_sonstige), the churn rate for non-registered users are lower than for the users, who completed the registration.

For the modelling part, it is good news that the churn rate differs for the different features here.

4.5 - NL-Columns¶

  • This data shows, in which of these newsletters a user is registered.
  • Values differ from 0 to 2.

    0 = not available
    1 = unsubscribed
    2 = active

  • There are three different Newsletters in this dataset: ZEITBRIEF, ZEITSHOP and ZEITVERLAG HAMBURG (ELBVERTIEFUNG)
  • A majority of 62.4% of our paying subs receive the Zeitbrief-Newsletter
  • 12.1% of the subscribers receive the Zeitshop-Newsletter
  • Only 4.8% of the subscribers receive the Zeitverlag-Newsletter

4.6 - Reg-Columns¶

This data shows, in which of these services a user is registered. Values differ from 0 to 1.
0 = not registered
1 = registered

boa_reg --> BOA: Berufsorientierung für Absolventen (job orientation for graduates)
che_reg --> CHE: Hochschullranking (College Ranking)
sit_reg --> SIT: Studium Interessentest (Study interest test)
sso_reg --> SSO: Single Sign On

Counts: Only for sso_reg there are more registrations than users, who didn't register. The single sign on authentification is necessary for various online services.

Churning rates:

  • The most significant differences between registered users and non-registered users can be found for boa_reg and sso_reg
  • For BOA: if the service helps graduates find a job quickly it is plausible that you keep your payed subscription because of higher purchasing power and because you benefited from this free to use Zeit-service

Vetragsdauer vs. Lesedauer:¶

as "Lesedauer" is generated on the randomly selected "date_x" for non-churners, we will add 2 more representative columns vertragsdauer_tage & vertragsdauer_monate:

  • as the most recent Data for "liefer_beginn_evt" is May 24th 2019 the shortest vertragsdauer_monate for non-churners is 12 months
  • a logic consequence: In the first 12 months we have a ratio of 100% churners an 0% retainers
    • the early-churners mostly have "Negative Option" or a "Probeabo", but also flexible subscription options that can be cancelled every month
  • for "vertragsdauer-monate" this results in a higher peak at the 13th & 14th months, the first time churners & non_churners get accumulated
  • lesedauer is basically smoothing the effects of the contract terms which is having a negative effect on our models
  • if you compare the
In [129]:
df['vertragsdauer_tage'] = (df['kuendigungs_eingangs_datum'] - df['liefer_beginn_evt']).dt.days
In [130]:
df['vertragsdauer_monate'] = df['vertragsdauer_tage'].apply(lambda x: x / 30).round().astype(int)
